{:proof/problem-id "lts-ultraproduct-thm1", :proof/version 1, :proof/canonical {:statement "Ultraproduct of factor algebras is isomorphic to factor of ultraproduct by ultraproduct of congruences.", :closure-criterion "Analytical proof", :statement-hash "sha256:dd26d4cdb89159b8582d9ff5e6fe78762246a5bf103d473b161700ae22a188a4", :version-history [{:version 1, :statement "Ultraproduct of factor algebras is isomorphic to factor of ultraproduct by ultraproduct of congruences.", :hash "sha256:dd26d4cdb89159b8582d9ff5e6fe78762246a5bf103d473b161700ae22a188a4", :changed-at "2026-03-29T18:22:46.331440315Z", :reason "Initial statement"}]}, :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove isomorphism", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/artifact-paths [], :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "lts-ultraproduct-thm1-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "The theorem states that $\\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(A_i / \\sigma(i)) \\cong \\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(A_i) / \\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(\\sigma(i))$. This is a commutation result: taking quotients commutes with ultraproducts. The key question is why the natural map between these two objects is well-defined, injective, and surjective."}, :propose {:approach "Construct the natural map and verify it is a well-defined isomorphism.", :notes "Define a map $\\Phi\\colon \\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(A_i) / \\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(\\sigma(i)) \\to \\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(A_i/\\sigma(i))$ by sending the equivalence class of $(a_i)_{i \\in I}$ modulo the ultraproduct of congruences to the ultraproduct of the equivalence classes $(a_i/\\sigma(i))_{i \\in I}$. Well-definedness follows from the ultrafilter structure. Bijectivity uses Los's theorem."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-ultraproduct"], :notes "Well-definedness: if $(a_i)$ and $(b_i)$ represent the same class modulo $\\Pi_{\\mathcal{D}}(\\sigma(i))$, then $\\{i : (a_i, b_i) \\in \\sigma(i)\\} \\in \\mathcal{D}$, so $\\{i : a_i/\\sigma(i) = b_i/\\sigma(i)\\} \\in \\mathcal{D}$, hence the images in the ultraproduct agree. Surjectivity: every element of the target is represented by some $(a_i/\\sigma(i))$, which is the image of $(a_i)$. Injectivity: if the images agree, Los gives the congruence condition back. Homomorphism property: operations commute with the quotient map coordinatewise."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["ok"], :notes "The proof uses three standard tools: (1) Los's theorem for transferring first-order properties through ultraproducts, (2) the universal property of quotient algebras, (3) the ultrafilter condition $\\{i : P(i)\\} \\in \\mathcal{D}$ as the bridge between coordinatewise and ultraproduct-level statements. No circularity."}, :classify {:classification :proved, :rationale "Analytical", :notes "This is a naturality result: the quotient construction is a functor, and ultraproducts preserve the functor's action. The deeper lesson is that ultraproducts, being filtered colimits of products, commute with many algebraic constructions. This generalises to any variety of algebras."}, :integrate {:rationale "Complete", :ledger-changes [{:item/id "root", :change :status-to-proved}], :notes "Exam-day field kit: (1) Los's theorem converts ultraproduct questions to coordinatewise questions modulo the ultrafilter. (2) Quotient maps are surjective homomorphisms. (3) The isomorphism theorem for algebras. The pattern: define the natural map, check well-definedness via the ultrafilter, check bijectivity via Los."}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :proved}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T18:22:46.339822434Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T18:22:46.392453611Z", :cycle/result-status :proved}], :proof/failed-routes [], :proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T18:22:46.331503266Z"}